<section class="evidence-band" aria-labelledby="case-architecture">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <p class="section-label">01 / Case Architecture</p>
    <h2 id="case-architecture">Vostok case comparison.</h2>
    <div class="manual-table-wrap">
      <table class="manual-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Case</th>
            <th scope="col">L2L</th>
            <th scope="col">Diameter</th>
            <th scope="col">Verdict</th>
            <th scope="col">Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">710 · Ministry</th>
            <td>~45mm</td>
            <td>~41mm</td>
            <td>Best balance</td>
            <td>Cushion shape, tapered profile, and enough presence for the wrist without losing comfort.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">170</th>
            <td>~46mm</td>
            <td>~42mm</td>
            <td>Strong</td>
            <td>Large on paper and on wrist; a useful bridge between the 710 and 090 families.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">090 · Tonneau</th>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>~42mm</td>
            <td>Strong</td>
            <td>Rectangular tonneau shape adds visual heft beyond the diameter figure.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">120</th>
            <td>~49mm</td>
            <td>~40mm</td>
            <td>Biggest L2L</td>
            <td>Tall relative to width; can read clunky despite the useful lug-to-lug number.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">100</th>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>40mm</td>
            <td>Solid</td>
            <td>12mm thick with 18mm lugs. Comfortable middle ground.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">420</th>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>~40mm</td>
            <td>Runs small</td>
            <td>Short lugs and no crown guards. Same dial options, less wrist presence.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">110</th>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>Skip</td>
            <td>Lugs do not curve down; rides high and does not suit the working target.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Komandirskie standard</th>
            <td>~37-40mm</td>
            <td>37-38mm</td>
            <td>Dress size</td>
            <td>30m water resistance only. Prefer Komandirskie 200m / 43-case crossover examples.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <aside class="manual-plate" aria-label="Dive case anatomy note">
      <p class="section-label">Fig. 1 / Anatomy of a dive case</p>
      <h3>Vostok 710 reference</h3>
      <dl class="manual-inline-list">
        <div><dt>Lug-to-lug</dt><dd>45mm</dd></div>
        <div><dt>Case diameter</dt><dd>41.6mm</dd></div>
        <div><dt>Lug width</dt><dd>22mm</dd></div>
      </dl>
      <p>Lug-to-lug predicts wrist presence more reliably than case diameter alone. A 40mm watch with short lugs can wear smaller than the number implies.</p>
    </aside>
  </div>
</section>

