<section class="source-band" aria-labelledby="field-instruments">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <p class="section-label">03 / Adjacent Field Instruments</p>
    <h2 id="field-instruments">Portable measurement, orientation, and timekeeping.</h2>
    <div class="directory-grid manual-instrument-grid">
      <article>
        <span>Compass</span>
        <h3>Adrianov Compass</h3>
        <p>Soviet Army wrist/pocket compass with mil-graduated dial, Bakelite or metal housing, and natural wrist pairing with a Vostok.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Compass</span>
        <h3>AK Artillery Compass</h3>
        <p>Adrianov sibling with hinged mirror cover for simultaneous orientation and angle reading. Mils, not degrees.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Wind</span>
        <h3>Soviet Anemometer</h3>
        <p>Manual wind-speed meter from the same material era as the watch collection. Working examples remain obtainable.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Calculation</span>
        <h3>Sun Hemmi Slide Rule</h3>
        <p>Bamboo-bodied Japanese pocket slide rule. Engineer/scientist kit before calculators; genuinely portable field instrument.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Time</span>
        <h3>Molnija 24h Pocket Watch</h3>
        <p>Caliber suffix 23/24 marks the rare 24-hour Molnija variant. Long-term rarity hunt.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Chronograph</span>
        <h3>Type 20 Chronograph</h3>
        <p>French Air Force flyback chronograph specification. Vintage examples are collector tier; modern reissues remain aspirational reference points.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

